      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the load increases at the very tip of the cantilevered balcony, the torque indeed increases linearly with respect to the distance from the pivot point. Since torque (τ) is calculated as the product of the force (F) and the distance (d) from the pivot point (τ = F * d), if the force (which in this case is the weight of the load) increases, the torque will increase proportionally. The relationship is linear, not exponential, because the torque is directly proportional to the force applied at a constant distance from the pivot.\n\nRegarding the internal stresses, as the load increases, the materials in the cantilevered balcony experience various types of stresses. The primary stress is bending stress, which occurs due to the bending moment created by the load. This bending moment causes the material to bend, and the fibers on the top side of the cantilever are in compression, while those on the bottom side are in tension.\n\nThe fixed connection at the wall must be able to resist these stresses without failing. The materials used, such as reinforced concrete, are chosen for their high compressive strength and sufficient tensile strength to handle the bending stresses. Additionally, the design of the connection, including the size and shape of the reinforcement",
